# zeroclaw Conventions

## Stack
- Rust (Cargo workspace with multiple crates)
- Trait-driven, modular architecture
- Extension via traits: Provider, Channel, Tool, Memory, Observer, Peripheral

## Key Commands
- Format check: `cargo fmt --all -- --check`
- Lint: `cargo clippy --all-targets -- -D warnings`
- Test: `cargo test`
- Full CI validation: `./dev/ci.sh all`

## Crate Map
- `zeroclaw-api` — public trait definitions (Provider, Channel, Tool, Memory, Observer, Peripheral)
- `zeroclaw-config` — schema, config loading/merging
- `zeroclaw-providers` — model providers and resilient wrapper
- `zeroclaw-channels` — messaging platform integrations (30+ channels)
- `zeroclaw-tools` — tool execution surface (shell, file, memory, browser)
- `zeroclaw-runtime` — agent loop, security, cron, SOP, skills, observability
- `zeroclaw-memory` — memory backends (markdown, sqlite, embeddings, vector merge)
- `zeroclaw-gateway` — webhook/gateway server (separate binary)
- `zeroclaw-hardware` — USB discovery, peripherals, serial, GPIO
- `zeroclaw-plugins` — WASM plugin system

## Rust Conventions
- Ownership and borrowing: follow Rust idioms strictly; do not fight the borrow checker.
- Error handling: use `Result<T, E>` with `?` propagation; avoid `unwrap()` in production code.
- Use `thiserror` for library error types, `anyhow` sparingly in binary/CLI code.
- All code must pass `clippy` with `-D warnings` (zero warnings policy).
- Prefer `impl Trait` for function parameters when the concrete type is not needed by callers.

## Risk Tiers
- High risk: `zeroclaw-runtime/src/` (especially security), `zeroclaw-gateway/src/`, `zeroclaw-tools/src/`, `.github/workflows/`
- Medium risk: most `crates/*/src/**` behavior changes
- Low risk: docs, chore, tests-only changes

## Workflow
- Read before write — inspect existing module, factory wiring, and adjacent tests.
- One concern per PR — no mixed feature+refactor patches.
- Implement minimal patch — no speculative abstractions.
- Work from a non-`master` branch; open a PR to `master`.
